a]]\n|death_date =\n|death_place =\n|nationality ={{USA}}\n|party =[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse =Joyce Schweikert (2006-)<ref name=Giblin2007/>\n|children =\n|residence =[[Fountain Hills, Arizona]]\n|alma_mater =[[Arizona State University]], [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]], [[M.B.A.]]\n|occupation =[[real estate broker]]\n|religion =[[Roman Catholic]]\n|signature =\n|website =[http://www.david10.com campaign website]\n}}\n\n'''David Schweikert''' (born March 3, 1962) is a member of the [[United States House of Representatives]] from [[Arizona]], serving since 2011. He is a member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].  He currently represents {{ushr|Arizona|6}}, which includes most of northern [[Phoenix, Arizona|Phoenix]] as well as [[Scottsdale, Arizona|Scottsdale]], [[Paradise Valley, Arizona|Paradise Valley]], and [[Cave Creek]].  He previously represented the [[Arizona's 5th congressional district|5th District]] from 2011 to 2013.\n\nHe previously served two terms in the [[Arizona State House of Representatives]] (1991&ndash;1994), was chairman of the state Board of Equalization (1995&ndash;2004), and was the elected [[Maricopa County]] Treasurer (2004&ndash;2007). He ran for the U.S. House of Representatives three times: losing a primary to [[J.D. Hayworth]] in 1994, losing the general election to incumbent [[Harry Mitchell]] in 2008, and then defeating Mitchell in 2010.\n\n==Early life, education, and business career==\nSchweikert was born in [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], but grew up in Scottsdale with his adoptive [[German American]]{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} parents and two adoptive siblings. He graduated from [[Saguaro High School]] there (1980), then earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] (finance and real estate, 1985) and [[MBA]] (2005) from the [[Arizona State University]]'s [[W. P. Carey School of Business]].\n\nSchweikert and his wife Joyce live in [[Fountain Hills, Arizona|Fountain Hills]].\n\n==Arizona House of Representatives (1991&ndash;1995)==\nSchweikert was elected to the [[Arizona State House of Representatives]] for District 28 in 1990, and re-elected in 1992.<ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/1990/General/Canvass1990GE.pdf\n |title=State of Arizona Official Canvass - General Election - November 6, 1990\n |accessdate=2009-04-21 |author= |first=Jim |last=Shumway |date=November 26, 1990\n |work= |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Arizona]]\n |page=7 |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=District 28 (Maricopa county) State Representative<br>Lisa Graham (R) 20,051<br>David Schweikert (R) 40,925<br>Bill Searle (D) 20,051}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/1992/General/Canvass1992GE.pdf 1992 |title=State of Arizona Official Canvass - General Election - November 3, 1992\n |accessdate=2009-04-21 |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |date=November 23, 1992\n |work= |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Arizona]]\n |page=7 |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=District 28 (Maricopa & Yavapai counties) State Representative<br>Lisa Graham (R) 47,936<br>David Schweikert (R) 33,285}}\n</ref><ref name=\"ar1\">\n{{Cite news\n |first=Matthew |last=Benson |author= |author2=Pitzl, Mary Jo |author3=Wingett, Yvonne\n  |title=Arizona primary results yield few surprises\n |url=http://www.azcentral.com/arizonarepublic/news/articles/2008/09/03/20080903elect-main0903.html\n |work=[[Arizona Republic]] |publisher= |location= |id= |pages= |page= |date=September 3, 2008 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=}}\n</ref> He represented Fountain Hills and part of Scottsdale. He arrived in the wake of the AzScam scandal, and was a committee chairman{{Citation needed|date=April 2009}} as a freshman and [[majority whip]] in his second term.<ref name=ATMA2007/> His consistently conservative record led [[Republican party (United States)|Republican]] colleagues to elevate him to [[Majority Whip]].\n\n==Local politics (1995&ndash;2007)==\nAs chair of the State Board of Equalization, Schweikert was also responsible for overseeing billions of dollars in valuations and tax protests from Arizona citizens and businesses.<ref>[http://www.azcentral.com/news/election/azelections/azfactcheck/fact-summary.php?candidate_id=36 AZ Fact Check], [[Arizona Republic]]</ref> There was speculation in 1999 that [[Arizona Governor]] [[Jane Dee Hull]] might appoint Schweikert to the Arizona State Corporation Commission.<ref>\n{{cite news|first=Paul |last=Davenport |authorlink=<!-- Paul Davenport but not ninth president of the University of Western Ontario--> |author= |title=Hull anxious to pick West substitute |url=http://news.google.com/newspapers?id=X8ALAAAAIBAJ&sjid=plUDAAAAIBAJ&pg=6504%2C6725037 |agency=Associated Press |publisher=Today's News-Herald |location=[[Lake Havasu City, Arizona]] |date=June 11, 1999 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |id= |pages= |page= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=The fractious Arizona Corporation Commission ... has been mired in controversy thanks to politics and personalities. Now, with Tony West's removal from the three-member commission, the need to wait for a replacement to be named by Gov. Jane Hull creates new uncertainty ... Names figuring in public speculation about the appointment include ... former state Rep. David Schweikert ....}} Vol 34, No 116</ref> He was appointed chairman of the Arizona State Board of Equalization, a full-time job, where he served from 1995-2003.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maricopa.gov/Clk_Board/PDF/BandCs/STATE_BOARD_OF_EQUALIZATION.pdf\n |title=State Board of Equalization |accessdate=2009-04-20 |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |date=3005-06-24\n |format=PDF |publisher=[[Maricopa County]] government |work= |pages= |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=...additional member designated as Chairperson by the Governor who shall serve in a full time capacity.}}</ref>\n\nHe was appointed Chief Deputy [[Treasurer]] of [[Maricopa County]] in 2004, and was elected Treasurer the same year. He resigned in 2007 to run for Congress again.<ref name=ATMA2007>\n{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |author= |title=Description of the 2nd Presentation on July 25, 2007 by David Schweikert Maricopa County Treasurer\n |url=http://www.arizonatooling.org/PDF%20FILES/Newsletters%202007/ATMA%20AprMayJune.pdf\n |format=PDF |work=PRECISION NEWS: The Newsletter of the Arizona Tooling & Machining Association\n |publisher=Arizona Tooling & Machining Association |location=\n |accessdate=2009-04-20\n |id= |pages= |page= |year=2007 |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=In December 2004, David Schweikert was sworn in as Maricopa County Treasurer. He has a B.S. degree in Finance/Real Estate and [an] MBA from W.P. Carey/Arizona State University. Before becoming Treasurer, David served as Chief Deputy Treasurer. Prior to that, he served as chairman of the Arizona State Board of Equalization.\nDavid has worked as an investment analyst and has been involved in the Real Estate industry and property tax issues for 25 years.\nIn 1990, David was elected to represent Northeast Maricopa County in the Arizona House of Representatives. In 1992 he was selected to the position of Majority Whip.}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}} Issue 2, 2007\n</ref><ref>\n{{cite web\n |url=http://sharp.sefora.org/people/house/david-schweikert/\n |title=David Schweikert - SHARP Network |accessdate=2009-04-20\n |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |work=SHARP (Science, Health and Related Policies) Network\n |publisher=[[Scientists and Engineers for America]]\n |pages= |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=}}\n</ref><ref name=Wingett2007>\n{{Cite news|first=Yvonne |last=Wingett\n |title=Maricopa County has new tax collector\n |url=http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/1114treasurer1114.html\n |work=[[The Arizona Republic]]\n |date=November 14, 2007 |accessdate=2009-04-20\n |publisher= |location= |id= |pages= |page= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate=\n |quote=Board of Supervisors appointed Charles \"Hos\" Hoskins the new county's treasurer. He replaces David Schweikert, who resigned on Oct. 22 to feel out a run for Congress.}}</ref> In 2008 he lost by 10 percentage points, 53-43%, to Democrat [[Harry Mitchell]] in congressional district 5. In 2010 he defeated the two term incumbent.\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives (2011&ndash;Present)==\n\n===Elections===\n;1994\nHe ran for the September 1994 Republican primary in [[Arizona's 6th congressional district]]. It resembled the 5th district formed after the [[2000 United States Census|2000 census]], but also included most of the northeastern part of the state, including [[Flagstaff, Arizona|Flagstaff]] and the [[Navajo reservation]]. \n[[J.D. Hayworth]] defeated him 45%-22%.<ref>{{Cite book |first=Michael |last=Barone |authorlink=Michael Barone (pundit) |author2=Ujifusa, Grant |editor= |others=[[Richard E. Cohen]] |title=[[The Almanac of American Politics]] |origdate= |origyear= |url= |accessdate=2009-04-20 |edition=1998 |series= |year=1997 |publisher=[[National Journal]] |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |language= |isbn=0-89234-080-0 |oclc= |doi= |id= |pages=87, 106 |page= |chapter=Arizona 6th District |chapterurl= |quote=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|first= |last= |authorlink= |author= |title=State of Arizona Official Canvass - Primary Election - September 13, 1994 |url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/1994/Primary/Canvass1994PE.pdf |format=PDF |work= |publisher=[[Secretary of State of Arizona]] |location=[[Phoenix, Arizona]] |id= |pages= |page= |date=September 26, 1994 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=<br> Karan English (D) 32,261<br> J.D. Hayworth (R) 21,109<br> Gary Husk (R) 6,500<br> Ramona Liston (R) 4,376<br> David Schweikert (R) 9,565<br> David Smith (R) 5,093<br> Sequoia R. Fuller (L) (write in) 37}}\n</ref>\nAfter that defeat, he took time to reconsider and left for a lengthy vacation, which included travel to [[Calcutta]], the [[Philippines]], [[Myanmar]], [[Nepal]], [[Vietnam]] and [[Serbia]].<ref name=Giblin2007>{{Cite news |first=Paul |last=Giblin |authorlink=Paul Giblin |author= |title=Ex-county treasurer to run again for Congress |url=http://www.eastvalleytribune.com/story/101257 |work=[[East Valley Tribune]] |publisher=[[Freedom Communications|Freedom Communications Inc]] |location=[[Mesa, Arizona]] |date=November 4, 2007 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |id= |pages= |page= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=In a real sense, losing improved his life, Schweikert said. Until then, he ran a real estate business, but threw most of his time and energy into politics. Suddenly, at 32, politics were out.}}</ref>\n\n;2008\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2008#District 5}}\nSchweikert won a six way Republican [[primary election]] September 2, 2008 with 30% of the vote, compared to 27% for his nearest rival, [[Susan Bitter-Smith]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/2008/Primary/Canvass2008PE.pdf |title=2008 primary election - September 2, 2008 |accessdate=2009-04-21 |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |date=September 15, 2008 |work=State of Arizona Official Canvas |publisher=[[Arizona Secretary of State]] |pages= |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate=}}</ref>\n\nSeveral organizations endorsed Schweikert in the 2008 election, including the primary election: [[Club for Growth]], the Arizona Police Association, Arizona [[Right to Life]], and the Arizona Medical Association. Schweikert later blamed his defeat on the very bitter primary fight that preceded it.<ref name=McArdle2009>{{Cite news|first=John |last=McArdle |authorlink=John McArdle |author= |title=Too Enticing a Target? |url=http://www.rollcall.com/issues/54_113/politics/33752-1.html?type=printer_friendly |work=[[Roll Call]] |publisher= |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |id= |pages= |page= |date=April 2, 2009 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=}} {{Dead link|date=November 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref> He received more than a half-million dollars from the [[Club for Growth]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/2007/11/club_pac_endorses_schweikert_i.php |title=Club for Growth PAC Endorses David Schweikert in Arizona-5 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |date=November 16, 2007 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |first= |last= |authorlink= |work= |publisher= [[Club for Growth]] |pages= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.clubforgrowth.org/2008/09/schweikert_wins_in_az05.php |title=Club for Growth PAC-Endorsed Candidate Wins in AZ-05 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |date=September 3, 2008 |location=[[Washington, D.C.]] |first= |last= |authorlink= |work= |publisher= [[Club for Growth]] |pages= |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=The former Maricopa County Treasurer topped a highly competitive field of six candidates to win the right to face freshman Harry Mitchell in the general election in November. The Club for Growth PAC bundled $337,000 in campaign contributions for Schweikert and spent over $200,000 in independent expenditures on his behalf.}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}\n</ref> He was endorsed by the Arizona Police Association, which includes [[Chandler, Arizona|Chandler]], [[Mesa, Arizona|Mesa]], and [[Tempe, Arizona|Tempe]] law enforcement agencies,<ref name=Club_for_growth>{{cite web |url=http://david08.com/whyDavid/index.cfm?&subsec=17 |archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20080211091450/http://www.david08.com/whyDavid/index.cfm?&subsec=17 |archivedate=February 11, 2008 |title=David Schweikert 08 - Why David? | publisher= david08.com}}</ref> the Arizona [[Right to Life]],<ref name=Club_for_growth/> the Arizona Medical Association{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} and the [[Citizens Against Government Waste]]'s [[political action committee]].<ref name=\"ar1\"/><ref>{{Cite news |title=CCAGW PAC Endorses David Schweikert for Arizona's 5th District |url=http://findarticles.com/p/articles/mi_m0EIN/is_2008_Oct_15/ai_n30906969/ |work=[[Business Wire]] |publisher= findarticles.com |date=October 15, 2008 |accessdate=2009-04-20 |first= |last= |authorlink= |author= |id= |pages= |page= |language= |archiveurl= |archivedate= |quote=The Council for Citizens Against Government Waste Political Action Committee (CCAGW PAC) today announced its endorsement of David Schweikert for Congress in Arizona's fifth Congressional District. Mr. Schweikert is running against Rep. Harry Mitchell.}}</ref>\n\nHe lost the [[general election]] to freshman [[incumbent]] [[Democratic party (United States)|Democrat]] [[Harry Mitchell]], 53%-44%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.azsos.gov/election/2008/General/Canvass2008GE.pdf |title=2008 General Election - November 4, 2008 |accessdate=2009-04-21 |author= |first= |last= |authorlink= |date=December 1, 2008 |work=State of Arizona Official Canvass |publisher=[[Arizona Secretary of State]] |pages= |language= |doi= |archiveurl= |archivedate=}}</ref>\n\n;2010\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2010#District 5}}\nSchweikert sought a rematch with Mitchell in 2010, with Libertarian Nick Coons also running. Schweikert won the Republican primary on August 24 with 29% of the vote. Early polling showed the race a dead heat. The Club for Growth decided to again endorse Schweikert after having sat out the competitive primary election.<ref>{{cite news|title=Club for Growth Backs Schweikert|url=http://www.usnews.com/preview/8-139878-arizona-club-for-growth-backs-schweikert|newspaper=CQ Politics|date=September 7, 2010|agency=US News & World Report}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 2010 Schweikert defeated two-term incumbent Congressman Harry Mitchell 52%-43%.\n\n;2012\n{{main|United States House of Representatives elections in Arizona, 2012#District 6}}\nAfter redistricting, the bulk of Schweikert's former territory became the [[Arizona's 9th congressional district|9th district]],<ref>[http://www.dailykos.com/story/2011/10/04/1022899/-Arizona-Redistricting-Commission-releases-draft-map Arizona Redistricting: Commission releases draft map]. [[Daily Kos]], 2011-10-04</ref> while his home in Fountain Hills was drawn into the newly created [[Arizona's 4th congressional district|4th district]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/New_Arizona_Lines_Mean_Battle_Between_GOP_Freshmen-209244-1.html|title=New Arizona Lines Mean Battle Between GOP Freshmen|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=November 27, 2012|work=[[Roll Call]] |first=Abby|last=Livingston}}</ref> However, as soon as the maps were released, Schweikert announced he would run in the 6th district. That district had previously been the 3rd, represented by fellow Republican freshman [[Ben Quayle]]. However, in a statement announcing his re-election plans, Schweikert pointed out that he'd grown up in Scottsdale\u2014most of which had been drawn into the 6th as well\u2014had represented it in both the state house and in Congress, and owned a second home there.<ref name=nj>{{cite web|url=http://hotlineoncall.nationaljournal.com/archives/2011/10/house-democrats.php |title=House Democrats Gain With New Arizona Map|date=October 5, 2011|accessdate=October 7, 2011|work=[[National Journal]]|first=Jessica|last=Taylor}}</ref> A revised map, however, placed Schweikert's home in Fountain Hills into the reconfigured 6th.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://atr.rollcall.com/quayle-chooses-to-run-against-schweikert/|title=Arizona: Quayle Opts to Run Against Schweikert |date= February 6, 2012|accessdate=February 7, 2012|work=[[Roll Call]] |first=Abby |last=Livingston}}</ref><ref>[http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/the-fix/wp/2012/08/29/schweikert-beats-quayle-in-arizona/ Schweikert defeats Quayle]</ref>\n\nQuayle, whose home in Phoenix had been drawn into the 9th but was just outside the boundaries of the 6th, opted to seek re-election in the 6th as well. During the bitter primary campaign, Schweikert was widely criticised for a mailer that accused Quayle of \"going both ways\", suggesting that he was bisexual. On the reverse, the mailer listed issues on which it claimed Quayle had taken both liberal and conservative positions. Senator [[Jon Kyl]] said that \"such campaign tactics insult the voters, degrade politics and expose those who stoop to them as unworthy of high office\" and Senator [[John McCain]] said the mailer was one of the \"worst that I have seen\" and that it \"crosses the boundary of decent political dialogue and discourse.\" Quayle's spokeswoman called the mailer \"utterly false\" and \"a sleazy smear tactic.\" Schweikert's spokesman responded that people \"should get their minds out of the gutter\" because the mailer was \"obviously\" referring to \"'both ways' -- as in liberal and conservative.\" ''[[The Arizona Republic]]'' asked two political scientists to review the mailer, who both said that they had \"never seen anybody accuse someone of flip-flopping [on political issues] that way\" and said that it was \"difficult to believe\" that the sexual suggestion was unintentional.<ref>http://dailycaller.com/2012/08/08/schweikert-quayle-goes-both-ways-on-important-conservative-issues/ Schweikert: Quayle \u2018goes both ways \u2026 on important conservative issues\u2019</ref><ref>http://www.bizjournals.com/phoenix/news/2012/08/06/kyl-faults-schweikert-after-mailer.html Kyl faults Schweikert after mailer says Quayle 'goes both ways'</ref><ref>http://www.azcentral.com/news/articles/2012/08/03/20120803district-6-schweikert-like-fight-in-dc.html District 6 race: David Schweikert says 'I like the fight' in D.C.</ref><ref>http://archive.azcentral.com/members/Blog/azdc/169420 McCain endorses Quayle, scolds Schweikert for mailer</ref><ref>http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/243973-mccain-blasts-arizona-republican-who-accused-quayle-of-going-both-ways McCain blasts Arizona Republican who accused Quayle of \u2018going both ways\u2019</ref>\n\nAlthough the 6th contained almost two-thirds of Quayle's constituents, Schweikert defeated Quayle in the Republican primary\u2014the real contest in this heavily Republican district\u2014by 53 percent to Quayle's 47 percent.<ref name=\"primary\">{{cite news |last=Zapler |first=Mike|last2=Isenstadt|first2=Alex|title=Arizona House primary results: Ben Quayle booted from Congress|url=http://www.politico.com/news/stories/0812/80331.html?hp=r2 |newspaper=Politico |date=August 29, 2012}}</ref> He won re-election to a second term with 62% of the vote.<ref>http://www.politico.com/2012-election/map/#/House/2012/AZ</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:David Schweikert by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Congressman Schweikert speaking at a rally in August 2014.]]\n;Immigration\nSchweikert argues that the state's immediate objective must be to secure the border against [[smuggling]] and [[illegal immigration]]. After it is \"truly secure,\" lawmakers can proceed to establish a \"common sense temporary [[guest worker]] program to enable businesses to obtain the employees they need.\" Additionally, Schweikert firmly opposes amnesty and \"[[sanctuary cities]].\"\n<ref name=\"david08.com\">{{cite web| title=2008 campaign website|url= http://www.david08.com/index.cfm | archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20080210134603/http://www.david08.com/index.cfm | archivedate= 2008-02-10}}</ref>\n\n;Defense\nSchweikert has said the government should make providing resources to national intelligence, the military and law enforcement a high priority.<ref name=\"david08.com\"/>\n\n;Firearms\nSchweikert opposes restrictions on gun ownership. He has received an \"A\" rating from both the [[National Rifle Association]] and [[Gun Owners of America]]. He was endorsed by the NRA in his 2010 election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.votesmart.org/candidate/106387/david-schweikert |title=Summary: Representative David Schweikert |publisher=Project Vote Smart |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Schweikert voted in favor of the National Right-To-Carry Reciprocity Act of 2011. This act requires all states, regardless of their own laws, to honor concealed carry permits from other states.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thomas.loc.gov/cgi-bin/query/z?c112:hr822: |title=H.R.822 - 112th Congress (2011-2012) |publisher=THOMAS (Library of Congress) |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Spending\nIn November 2011, Schweikert wrote a letter to President Obama objecting to $70,000 spent by the State Department on books authored by Obama, asking the President return the royalties.<ref>{{cite web |last=Cohn |first=Alicia M. |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/blog-briefing-room/news/191095-rep-schweikert-asks-obama-to-return-book-royalties |title=Rep. Schweikert asks Obama to return book royalties |publisher= The Hill |date=November 1, 2011 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Embassies used the books as gratuity gifts and also to stock libraries in various countries.\n\nSchweikert believes that economic prosperity hinges on balancing the federal budget and making \"hard choices\" on entitlement programs like Medicare and Social Security.<ref>{{cite web|first=David |last=Schweikert |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/congress-blog/campaign/144187-what-happened-to-the-calculator |title=What happened to the calculator? |publisher=The Hill |date=February 15, 2011 |accessdate=February 24, 2012}}</ref>\n\n;Abortion\nSchweikert is strongly pro-life as proven by his vote for the Title X Abortion Provider Act, an Act that would deny all federal funding to Planned Parenthood. In addition, he voted yes for the No Taxpayer Funding for Abortion Act in which the Act would ban any taxpayer from funding abortions.<ref name=\"Vote Smart- David Schweikert\">{{cite web|title=David Schweikert|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/106387/david-schweikert/|publisher=Vote Smart|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref>  After his birth mother decided against an abortion, she gave birth to him at an unwed mother\u2019s home where he was adopted.<ref name=DailyCaller>{{cite news|last=Schweikert|first=David|title=Why I am pro-life|url=http://dailycaller.com/2012/01/21/why-i-am-pro-life/|accessdate=28 June 2013|newspaper=Daily Caller|date=2012-01-21}}</ref>\n\nWhen asked about his stance on abortion, Schwiekert said \"In a still struggling economy, when our top priority should be creating jobs and paying down our debt, taxpayers need not be asked to open their checkbooks for such a controversial cause. Especially if that cause is taking the life of an innocent unborn child.\"<ref name=\"Vote Smart- David Schweikert\" />\n\n;Balancing the budget\nSchweikert is against an income tax increase on any tax bracket: he signed Americans for Americans for Tax Reform: The Taxpayer Protection Pledge. The Taxpayer Protection Pledge is a pledge that many GOP candidates signed stating that they will oppose any and all efforts to increase the income tax rates for individuals and/or businesses, and oppose any net reduction or elimination of deductions and\ncredits, unless matched dollar for dollar by further reducing tax rates.<ref name=\"Vote Smart- David Schweikert\" />   [[FreedomWorks]], a \"lower taxes, less taxes, more freedom\" interest group, endorsed Schweikert in the 2012 general election.<ref name=\"Vote Smart- David Schweikert\" />\n\n;Environment and energy policy\nSchweikert voted yes on Opening the [[Continental shelf]] to oil drilling and voted yes for drilling in [[Arctic National Wildlife Refuge]], in pursuit of coal. He voted to bar the [[Environmental Protection Agency]] from regulating [[greenhouse gas]]es.<ref name=\"David Schweikert Enviornmental Stance\">{{cite web|title=David Schweikert|url=http://www.ontheissues.org/house/David_Schweikert.htm |publisher=Jesse Gordon- OntheIssues.org|accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref><ref>http://americansforprosperity.org/noclimatetax//wp-content/uploads/2010/06/schweikert.pdf</ref>\n\nSchweikert signed the American's For Prosperity \"No Climate Tax Pledge\" in which he will \"oppose any legislation relating to climate change that includes a net increase in government revenue\".<ref name= \"David Schweikert Enviornmental Stance\">{{cite web|title=David Schweikert |url= http://www.ontheissues.org/house/David_Schweikert.htm|publisher=Jesse Gordon- OntheIssues.org |accessdate=20 November 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nFor the [[113th United States Congress]], Schweikert is now serving on the following committees:<ref>http://schweikert.house.gov/committee-assignments/</ref>\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Science, Space and Technology]]'''\n\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Small Business]]'''\n** [[United States House Small Business Subcommittee on Investigations, Oversight and Regulations]] (Chairman)\n\nThe House Republican Steering Committee removed Schweikert from the Committee on Financial Services in late 2012 as part of a larger party leadership-caucus shift.<ref>Wing, Nick, [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/12/12/tim-huelskamp-john-boehner_n_2285196.html  \"Tim Huelskamp: John Boehner Guilty Of 'Petty, Vindictive Politics' In Committee Ousters\"], ''The Huffington Post'', 12/12/2012.</ref><ref name=WP01>Weiner, Rachel, [http://www.washingtonpost.com/blogs/post-politics/wp/2012/12/05/conservatives-bite-back-at-gop-leadership-over-purge/ \"Conservatives bite back over House GOP purge\"], Washington ''Post'' Post Politics blog, December 5, 2012. Retrieved 2013-01-02.</ref> He joined [[Justin Amash]] of Michigan and [[Tim Huelskamp]] of Kansas in a letter to [[Speaker of the United States House of Representatives|Speaker of the House]] [[John Boehner]], demanding to know why they had lost their \"plum\" committee posts.<ref>{{cite  web| title= Booted from plum committee seats, three GOP reps want answers| date= December 8, 2012 | url= http://politicalticker.blogs.cnn.com/2012/12/08/booted-from-plum-committee-seats-three-gop-reps-want-answers/ | first= Gregory|last= Wallace| publisher= CNN | work= Political Ticker (blog)| accessdate=2012-12-08}}</ref>\n\n''[[Politico]]'' quoted a spokesperson for Republican Congressman [[Lynn Westmoreland]] of Georgia as explaining that Schweikert, Amash and Huelskamp were removed for \"their inability to work with other members.\" The spokesperson clarified that Westmoreland \"said that it had nothing to do with their voting record, a scorecard, or their actions across the street [meaning fundraising].\" The three were described by ''Politico'' and its sourcing of Huelskamp's other colleagues as \"jerks\" who \"made life harder for other Republicans by taking whacks at them in public for supporting the team\".<ref name=\"The a\u2014hole factor\">{{ cite news | last=Allen |first=Jonathan | url=http://www.politico.com/story/2012/12/house-leaders-make-examples-of-obstinate-members-85034.html | title='The a\u2014hole factor' | publisher=Politico | date=December 13, 2012 | accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"'Obstinate' Factor Continues to Roil GOP\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rollcall.com/news/obstinate_factor_continues_to_roil_gop-219926-1.html|title='Obstinate' Factor Continues to Roil GOP|date=December 12, 2012|accessdate=April 30, 2014|publisher=Roll Call}}</ref>{{rp|p.2}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://schweikert.house.gov/ Congressman David Schweikert] official U.S. House site\n* [http://www.david10.com/ David Schweikert for Congress]\n*{{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Arizona/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/David_Schweikert_%5BR-6%5D}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio = S001183 | ballot = David_Schweikert | nndb = 951/000266153 | votesmart = 106387 | govtrack = 412399 | opencong = 412399 | rollcall = 3723 | politifact = | fec = H4AZ06045 | opensecrets = N00006460 | assets = david-schweikert |